# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adas-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] First introduced in the 1990s, ACC has evolved from early laser based systems to more advanced radar and camera-based technologies capable of operating at a full speed ranges, including stop-and-go traffic.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] ACC is considered a key component of partially automated driving.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Under SAE International's classification, most ACC systems are categorized as Level 1 automation, as they control longitudinal vehicle motion but require continuous driver supervision and do not provide full vehicle autonomy.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] When combined with steering assistance features such as lane centering, the system may qualify as Level 2 automation.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Adaptive cruise control (ACC) is an advanced driver-assistance feature that supplements, but does not replace, the role of the driver.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] The system automates longitudinal vehicle control by adjusting throttle and, in many systems, applying braking to maintain a preset following distance, but it requires continuous driver supervision and does not replace the driver's responsibility for vehicle operation.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] During operation, the driver selects a desired cruising speed and following distance.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] If the vehicle approaches slower-moving traffic, ACC automatically reduces engine power and may apply braking to maintain the selected gap.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] When traffic conditions permit, the vehicle accelerates back to the preset speed.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Some full speed range systems are capable of functioning in stop-and-go traffic, though driver attention remains required.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Adaptive cruise control is commonly offered as standard equipment on higher trim levels, or as part of optional safety or technology packages.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] The inclusion of ACC may increase a vehicle's price by several hundred to several thousand U.S. dollars depending on the manufacturer and the features bundled with the system.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Because ACC is frequently packaged with other ADAS technologies, such as lane-keeping assist or automatic emergency braking, buyers may pay for a broader safety suite rather than the feature as a standalone option.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] ACC systems are commonly distinguished by the sensing technologies used to detect and track vehicles ahead, most often radar, lidar, cameras, or combinations of these sensors.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Radar-based sensors work by emitting a radio wave at a frequency of either 24 GHz or 77 GHz.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] As these signals are emitted, the car computes how long it takes for the signal to return, thus finding out how far away a vehicle may be in front of it.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Due to the widely distributed beam, radar ACC systems allow for a much wider field of view while still being able to provide accurate measurements of 160+ meters (Roughly 525 feet).
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] These radar systems can be hidden behind plastic fascias; however, the fascias may look different from a vehicle without the feature.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] For example, Mercedes-Benz packages the radar behind the upper grille in the center and behind a solid plastic panel that has painted slats to simulate the look of the rest of the grille.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Single radar systems are the most common.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Systems involving multiple sensors use either two similar hardware sensors like the 2010 Audi A8 or the 2010 Volkswagen Touareg, or one central long range radar coupled with two short radar sensors placed on the corners of the vehicle like the BMW 5 and 6 series.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Laser-based systems work using LIDAR (Light detection and ranging), allowing laser-based ACC to provide the largest detection distance as well as the best accuracy of all ACC systems.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] However, laser-based systems do not detect and track vehicles as reliably in adverse weather conditions due to the fact that fog, or water particles in the air may absorb and or redirect the light emitted from the laser, through absorption, scattering, and reflection.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Laser based ACC systems also have a more difficult time tracking dirty (and therefore non-reflective) vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Laser-based sensors must be exposed, the sensor (a fairly large black box) is typically found in the lower grille, offset to one side.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Camera-based adaptive cruise control (ACC) uses one or more forward-facing cameras to detect and track vehicles ahead using computer vision.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Instead of directly measuring range with reflected radio waves (radar) or laser pulses (lidar), camera-based systems infer distance and closing speed from image cues such as object size and motion across frames, and when stereo cameras are used, by estimating depth from parallax between two views.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Some camera-based ACC implementations use **stereo (binocular)** camera arrangements mounted near the windshield, enabling depth perception without radar.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Subaru's EyeSight is a well-known example of this approach; Subaru describes EyeSight as using camera-based sensing to support adaptive cruise control and related driver-assistance functions.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Other systems use **multiple cameras** with machine-learning-based perception.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Tesla’s “Tesla Vision” is a camera-dominant approach in which vehicles rely primarily on onboard cameras and neural-network processing for adaptive cruise control and other driver-assistance features.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Some ACC systems combine multiple sensor types, most commonly radar and cameras, to improve vehicle detection and tracking across varying conditions.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In such systems, radar provides robust range and relative-speed measurements, while cameras provide additional visual context for object classification and scene interpretation.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Predictive adaptive cruise control (PACC) builds on conventional ACC by incorporating forward-looking data and behavioral estimation to modify vehicle speed in anticipation of upcoming conditions.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Rather than reacting only to the distance and relative speed of a preceding vehicle, predictive systems use additional information to adjust speed proactively.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In production vehicles, PACC uses navigation and map data to anticipate roadway features.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Some systems incorporate GPS location data, digital maps, and traffic sign recognition to automatically adjust vehicle speed in response to upcoming curves, changes in speed limits, or highway exits.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] By combining sensor input with navigation information, the system can reduce speed before reaching a lower speed zone or approaching a bend, rather than responding after the change occurs.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] These predictive functions are typically implemented as part of a broader driver-assistance package, such as Ford Blue Cruise, GM Super Cruise, or Tesla Autopilot.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] These systems integrate adaptive cruise control with lane centering, high-precision maps, and driver-monitoring to enable wider autonomy features on compatible roads, distinguishing them from basic ACC implementations.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Guidance from U.S. and insurance-industry safety organizations emphasize that these systems remain assistance features and still require active driver supervision.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] The standard defines ACC as a partial automation of longitudinal vehicle control and distinguishes between **Full Speed Range Adaptive Cruise Control (FSRA)** and **Limited Speed Range Adaptive Cruise Control (LSRA)** systems.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Because ACC systems may automatically apply braking, they must also comply with applicable vehicle braking regulations.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In countries applying the UNECE framework, braking performance and electronic braking control requirements are governed by **UN Regulation No.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] 13-H**, which sets safety and performance standards for passenger car braking systems.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] ACC systems that provide active brake control must operate within the limits prescribed by these braking regulations.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Adaptive cruise control developed during the 1990s as an extension of conventional cruise control, initially focusing on forward distance detection rather than full longitudinal automation.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Early systems relied on lidar sensors and were limited to warning functions or throttle control without automatic braking.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] By the late 1990s and early 2000s, radar-based systems capable of modulating both throttle and braking began to appear in production vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Over time, manufacturers expanded ACC functionality to include full-speed-range stop-and-go operation, integration with collision mitigation systems, and, later, coordination with lane-centering features.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] By the mid-2010s, adaptive cruise control had become a core component of Level 2 driver-assistance systems and was increasingly offered as standard equipment across vehicle segments.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In 1999, Mercedes introduced Distronic, the first radar-assisted adaptive system, on the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W220) and the CL-Class.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Distronic adjusts the vehicle speed automatically to the car in front in order to always maintain a safe distance to other cars on the road.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In 2005, Mercedes refined the system ("Distronic Plus") making the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W221) the first car to receive the upgraded system.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Distronic Plus could now completely halt the car if necessary on most sedans.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In an episode of *Top Gear*, Jeremy Clarkson demonstrated the effectiveness of the system by coming to a complete halt from motorway speeds to a round-about and getting out, without touching the pedals.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In 2016, Mercedes introduced Active Brake Assist 4, the first emergency braking assistant with pedestrian recognition.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] One crash caused by Distronic Plus dates to 2005, when the German news magazine *Stern* was testing Mercedes' original Distronic system.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] During the test, the system did not always manage to brake in time.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Ulrich Mellinghoff, then Head of Safety, NVH, and Testing at the Mercedes-Benz Technology Centre, stated that some tests failed because the vehicle was tested in a metallic hall, which caused problems with radar.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] Later iterations received an upgraded radar and other sensors, which are not disrupted by a metallic environment.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] In 2008, Mercedes conducted a study comparing the crash rates of Distronic Plus vehicles and vehicles without it, and concluded that those equipped with Distronic Plus have an around 20% lower crash rate.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] For some models of cars, Comma.ai offers an aftermarket alternative to factory-built ACC systems through its openpilot software paired with Comma hardware.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] When installed in a compatible vehicle, OpenPilot replaces or adds to existing ADAS features.
[src:adas-systems/adaptive-cruise-control] This effectively brings Level-2 capabilities to some cars that originally did not have them.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] As most road crashes occur due to human error, ADAS are developed to automate, adapt, and enhance vehicle technology for safety and better driving.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS is proven to reduce road fatalities by minimizing human error.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Safety features are designed to avoid crashes and collisions by offering technologies that alert the driver to problems, implementing safeguards, and taking control of the vehicle if necessary.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to the national crash database in the US, forward collision prevention systems have the potential to reduce crashes by 29%.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Similarly, lane keeping assistance is shown to offer a reduction potential of 19%, while blind zone detection could decrease crash incidents by 9%.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to a 2021 research report from Canalys, approximately 33% of new vehicles sold in the United States, Europe, Japan, and China had ADAS.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The firm also predicted that 50% of all automobiles on the road by the year 2030 would be ADAS-enabled.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Some groups advocate standardization of the name, such as "forward collision warning" and "automatic emergency braking", rather than "forward collision alert" or "smart city brake support".
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Such standardization is promoted by AAA, Consumer Reports, J.D.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Power, National Safety Council, PAVE, and SAE International.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] After WWII, an engineer named Nathaniel Korman, who worked on radar systems during WWII, experimented with a system to control the speed of a train based on the speed of a train in front of it, using radar.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] He noted that it could also be used for on-road vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In 1948, Ralph Teetor applied for a US patent in a "speed control device for resisting operation of the accelerator", or what is now known as cruise control, granted in 1950.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] General Motors later displayed a concept car in 1959, which used some variation of the system, with radar embedded in the front nacelles of the car.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS were first used in production vehicles in the 1970s with the adoption of the anti-lock braking system.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Early ADAS include electronic stability control, anti-lock brakes, blind spot information systems, lane departure warning, adaptive cruise control, and traction control.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems can be affected by mechanical alignment adjustments or damage from a collision.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This has led many manufacturers to require automatic resets for these systems after a mechanical alignment is performed.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The reliance on data that describes the outside environment of the vehicle, compared to internal data, differentiates ADAS from driver-assistance systems (DAS).
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS rely on inputs from multiple data sources, including automotive imaging, LiDAR, radar, image processing, computer vision, telemetry, and in-car networking.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Additional inputs are possible from other sources separate from the primary vehicle platform, such as telematics data from other vehicles (vehicle-to-vehicle or V2V communication) and infrastructure (vehicle-to-infrastructure or V2I communication).
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Modern cars have ADAS integrated into their electronics; manufacturers can add these new features during the design process or after production via over-the-air (OTA) updates.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS are considered real-time systems since they react quickly to multiple inputs and prioritize the incoming information to prevent crashes.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The systems use preemptive priority scheduling to organize which task needs to be done first.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The incorrect assignment of these priorities is what can cause more harm than good.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The SAE classification of levels is based on the role of the driver, rather than the vehicle's capabilities, although these are related in the form of a "driving mode" (also known as a "driving scenario").
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The mode is determined by both an operational design domain (ODD) and a "dynamic driving requirement".
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The ODD is the circumstance in which the car is driving, and the driving requirement is what the system must do while remaining safe within the boundaries of that ODD.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] While most ADAS features are installed by the vehicle manufacturer during production (OEM), there is a growing market for aftermarket systems that can be retrofitted to existing vehicles, particularly in commercial fleets.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems are designed to provide key safety alerts and warnings to drivers of vehicles that were not originally equipped with ADAS.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The most common type of aftermarket ADAS is based on computer vision and utilizes a windshield-mounted camera.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This device, which often combines the functionality of a dashcam with ADAS software, continuously scans the road ahead.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Sometimes they are referred as AI Dashcams.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems are often a component of modern video telematics, as they not only provide safety alerts but also record video footage of the events.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This data is then transmitted via a telematic control unit to a fleet management platform, where it can be used for driver coaching and incident analysis.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This list is not a comprehensive list of all of the ADAS.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Instead, it provides information on critical examples of ADAS that have progressed and become more commonly available since 2015.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Ford and General Motors provide "hands-off, eyes-on" systems such as Blue Cruise and Super Cruise in North America.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems allow drivers to take their hands off the steering wheel while the system is engaged.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] However, drivers must keep their eyes on the road and be ready to take immediate action at all times.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In Europe, in Q2 2018, 3% of sold passenger cars had Level 2 autonomy driving features.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In Europe, in Q2 2019, 325,000 passenger cars are sold with Level 2 autonomy driving features, that is 8% of all new cars sold.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to a 2021 research report from Canalys, approximately 33 percent of new vehicles sold in the United States, Europe, Japan, and China had ADAS features.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The firm also predicted that fifty percent of all automobiles on the road by the year 2030 would be ADAS-enabled.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Major car brands with Level 2 features include Lexus, Audi, BMW, Mercedes-Benz, Tesla, Volvo, Tata, Citroën, Ford, Hyundai, Kia, Mazda, Nissan, Peugeot, Mahindra and Subaru.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Full Level 2 features are included with Full Self-Driving from Tesla, Pilot Assist from Volvo, OpenPilot from Comma.ai and ProPILOT Assist from Nissan.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Level 3 features are included in Honda Sensing Elite from Honda and Drive Pilot from Mercedes-Benz.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] SGO 2021-01 subsequently was amended on August 5, 2021.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] SGO 2021-01 is in effect for three years, starting on June 29, 2021.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] After gathering data for almost a year (July 1, 2021 through May 15, 2022), the NHTSA released the initial set of data in June 2022 and stated they plan to update the data on a monthly basis.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Of the 130 crashes, 108 had no associated injuries reported; there was only one serious injury associated with the remaining crashes.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The most commonly-reported damage location was the rear of the ADS-equipped vehicle.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Similarly, ADAS (Level 2) from 12 different manufacturers were involved in 367 crashes over the same period; 392 crashes were reported in total, but 25 either occurred before July 2021 or had no associated date.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Reported incidents were led by Tesla (273), Honda (90), and Subaru (10).
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Of the 392 crashes, 98 included injury reporting; of the 98, 46 had no injuries reported, 5 resulted in serious injuries and 6 resulted in fatalities.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The most commonly-reported damage location was the front of the ADAS-equipped vehicle.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] According to PACTS, lack of full standardization may make ADAS in different cars difficult for drivers to understand.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Button names and locations, as well as dashboard symbols, change from car to car due to lack of standardization.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS might have many limitations, for instance a pre-collision system might have 12 pages to explain 23 exceptions where ADAS may operate when not needed and 30 exceptions where ADAS may not operate when a collision is likely.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Names for ADAS features are not standardized.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] For instance, adaptive cruise control is called *Adaptive Cruise Control* by Fiat, Ford, GM, VW, Volvo and Peugeot, but *Intelligent Cruise Control* by Nissan, *Active Cruise Control* by Citroen and BMW, and *DISTRONIC* by Mercedes.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] To help with standardization, SAE International has endorsed a series of recommendations for generic ADAS terminology for car manufacturers, created with Consumer Reports, the American Automobile Association, J.D.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS behavior might change from car to car as well; for instanc,e ACC speed might be temporarily overridden in most cars, while some switch to standby after one minute.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The AV industry is growing exponentially, and according to a report by Market Research Future, the market is expected to hit over $65 billion by 2027.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] AV insurance and rising competition are expected to fuel that growth.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Auto insurance for ADAS has directly affected the global economy, and many questions have arisen within the general public.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS allow autonomous vehicles to enable self-driving features, but there are associated risks with ADAS.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] AV companies and manufacturers are recommended to have insurance in the following areas in order to avoid any serious litigations.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Depending on the level, ranging from 0 to 5, each car manufacturer would find it in its best interest to find the right combination of different insurances to best match their products.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Note that this list is not exhaustive and may be constantly updated with more types of insurances and risks in the years to come.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] With the technology embedded in autonomous vehicles, these self-driving cars are able to distribute data if a car crash occurs.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This, in turn, will invigorate the claims administration and their operations.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Fraud reduction will also disable any fraudulent staging of car crashes by recording the car's monitoring of every minute on the road.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS are expected to streamline the insurance industry and its economic efficiency with capable technology to fight off fraudulent human behavior.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In September 2016, the NHTSA published the Federal Automated Vehicles Policy, which describes the U.S.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Department of Transportation's policies related to highly automated vehicles (HAV) which range from vehicles with ADAS features to autonomous vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In March 2014, the US Department of Transportation's National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) announced that it will require all new vehicles under 10,000 pounds (4,500 kg) to have rear view cameras by May 2018.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The rule was required by Congress as part of the Cameron Gulbransen Kids Transportation Safety Act of 2007.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The Act is named after two-year-old Cameron Gulbransen.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The advancement of autonomous driving is accompanied by ethical concerns.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The earliest moral issue associated with autonomous driving can be dated back to as early as the age of the trolleys.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The trolley problem is one of the most well-known ethical issues.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Before the development of autonomous vehicles, the trolley problem remains an ethical dilemma between utilitarianism and deontological ethics.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] However, as the advancement in ADAS proceeds, the trolley problem becomes an issue that needs to be addressed by the programming of self-driving cars.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The crashes that autonomous vehicles might face could be very similar to those depicted in the trolley problem.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Although ADAS make vehicles generally safer than only human-driven cars, crashes are unavoidable.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Many researchers have been working on ways to address the ethical concerns associated with ADAS.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] For instance, the artificial intelligence approach allows computers to learn human ethics by feeding them data regarding human actions.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Such a method is useful when the rules cannot be articulated because the computer can learn and identify the ethical elements on its own without precisely programming whether an action is ethical.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] However, there are limitations to this approach.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] For example, many human actions are done out of self-preservation instincts, which is realistic but not ethical; feeding such data to the computer cannot guarantee that the computer captures the ideal behavior.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Furthermore, the data fed to an artificial intelligence must be carefully selected to avoid producing undesired outcomes.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Another notable method is a three-phase approach proposed by Noah J.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] This approach first necessitates a system established with the agreement of car manufacturers, transportation engineers, lawyers, and ethicists, and should be set transparently.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The second phase is letting artificial intelligence learn human ethics while being bound by the system established in phase one.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Lastly, the system should provide constant feedback that is understandable by humans.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In October 2023, Consumer Reports rated 17 "active driving assistance systems".
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] In March 2024, the American Insurance Institute for Highway Safety (IIHS) reported its first "partial automation safeguard ratings".
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Intelligent transportation systems (ITS) highly resemble ADAS, but go beyond automatic traffic to include any enterprise that safely transports humans, such as public transport.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] With ITS, transportation technology is integrated with a city's infrastructure.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] These systems promote active safety by increasing the efficiency of roads, possibly by adding 22.5% capacity on average.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ADAS have aided in this increase in active safety, according to a study in 2008.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] ITS use a wide system of communication technology, including wireless technology and traditional technology, to enhance productivity.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] A draft ADAS regulation named *driver control assistance systems* (DCAS) would allow hands-free driving with a possible risk of lack of attentiveness.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] Such DCAS regulation would allow system such as Tesla FSD in Europe.
[src:adas-systems/advanced-driver-assistance-system] The UNECE driver control assistance systems regulation plan that DCAS shall be designed to ensure that the driver performs the driving task, that the driver's hands must remain on the wheel and that the system shall monitor the driver's visual engagement.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] An **automotive night vision** system uses a thermographic camera to increase a driver's perception and seeing distance in darkness or poor weather beyond the reach of the vehicle's headlights.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Automotive night vision systems generally rely on infrared sensors, which detect energy on the infrared spectrum.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] This allows the vehicle to perceive heat signatures from pedestrians and animals in dark conditions.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Such systems are offered as optional equipment on certain premium vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Incorporating night vision technology adds to the growing complexity of modern vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] These systems require Electronic Control Units (ECUs) to process the raw data, which then must be integrated into the vehicle's existing data networks to function reliably with the engine and powertrain.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The technology was first introduced in the year 2000 on the Cadillac Deville.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] This technology is based on the night vision devices (NVD), which generally denotes any electronically enhanced optical devices operate in three modes: image enhancement, thermal imaging, and active illumination.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The automotive night vision system is a combination of NVDs such as infrared cameras, GPS, Lidar, and Radar, among others to sense and detect objects.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Recent advancements have expanded automotive thermal imaging beyond driver displays, and are now being included in the sensor suites of autonomous vehicles and Advanced Driver Assistance Systems (ADAS).
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] There are two types of systems, either passive or active systems, both have advantages and disadvantages when compared to the other.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The passive system pertains to the technologies that detect thermal radiation emitted by humans, animals, and other objects in the road while the active systems illuminate objects as a significant distance ahead using infrared light sources.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Active systems use an infrared light source built into the car to illuminate the road ahead with light that is invisible to humans.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] There are two kinds of active systems: gated and non-gated.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The gated system uses a pulsed light source and a synchronized camera that enable long ranges (250m) and high performance in rain and snow.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Near Infrared wavelength is 0.75–1.4 µm is smaller and can pass between the typical fog particles.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Fog particles sizes are typically 10 to 15 microns and ranges is sizes from 1 to 100 microns.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Far infrared has a wavelength of 15 micrometers (µm) to 1 mm.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] During night-time operations, police officers with range gated near infrared cameras can read license plates at a distance of up to 1.2 km.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Near Infrared (NIR) cameras are available to see 50 km through fog, haze, smoke, rain.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Series production Night View Assist system introduced in 2005 on the redesigned Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W221).
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] It was the first system to use the instrument cluster's LCD as a display.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] 2009: **Night View Assist Plus** added a pedestrian detection function calling the revised system on the redesigned Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W212) and refreshed S-class, however, the E-class uses the navigation screen's display.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] 2011: **Night View Assist Plus with Spotlight Function** premiere: the Mercedes-Benz CL-Class (C216) became the first series production car with night vision-guided pedestrian spotlighting (**HID** version) can flash at any pedestrians it detects in order to warn both the driver and the pedestrians.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The flashing light is directed in such a way that vehicles in front and oncoming traffic are not dazzled.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] 2013: Night View Assist Plus with **animal detection** on the W222 S-Class.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] In 2002 Toyota **Night View** was the first worldwide series production **active** automotive night vision system, introduced optionally on the Toyota Landcruiser Cygnus or Lexus LX470.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] This system first uses the near infrared light projectors placed next to the fog lights emitting near infrared light aimed like the car's high beam headlights.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Then, a CCD camera behind the rear view mirror captures that reflected infrared light, and then this signal is processed by the computer which produces a monochromatic image which is projected right above the gauge cluster onto the windshield.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] In February 2008 the Toyota Crown Hybrid added a feature which highlights pedestrians and presents them in a box on an LCD in front of the driver.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] This was the first pedestrian detection feature for an active system.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] In 2009, Lexus introduced Night View on the LS, but only in Japan.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] In 2012 Lexus introduced Night View worldwide, on LS and GS.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The Night View system combines a windshield mounted near infra-red camera and near infra-red projectors within the headlamps with a Night View ECU to display an image of the road ahead on center console display screen.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Moving the image from the driver’s instrument display to the center console offers drivers a larger display and an easier viewing angle.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] With the camera constantly in operation and the near infra-red projectors activating at speeds over 10 MPH to enhance system efficiency, night view will display an area up to 65 feet in front of the vehicle.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] This system was discontinued for 2014 in the US.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Passive infrared systems do not use an infrared light source, instead they capture thermal radiation already emitted by the objects, using a thermographic camera.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] 2008 update added **pedestrian detection** system on the redesigned BMW 7 Series (F01), which flashes a caution symbol on the navigation/information screen and automotive head-up display when it detects pedestrians.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] This updated system automatically scans up to 100 yards ahead of the vehicle when it reaches 25 mph, and applies a yellow tint to the pedestrians on the head-up display.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] 2013 update added **Dynamic Light Spot**.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The system provides a real-time video image that also depicts on the Control Display persons, animals and other objects emitting heat when they are outside of the light beam and warns in the event of an impending collision.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The Dynamic Light Spot is produced by a special headlight that directs the light beam onto the recognised persons or animals respectively, thus drawing the driver’s attention to possible hazards in good time.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] As soon as the remote infrared detects pedestrians or larger animals on course for collision in the dark, the system directs two separately controlled Dynamic Light Spots at them without creating an unpleasant glare.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] In the event of an acute risk, an acoustic warning signal is also sounded and the brakes are set to maximum standby.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] For the model year 2014, the BMW 5 Series will also have these new features.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] First worldwide series production automotive night vision on 2000 Cadillac Deville: **Night Vision**, however it was discontinued in 2004.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] This system was developed with Raytheon and worked by using a *passive infrared* sensor camera mounted behind the vehicle's grille.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Infrared radiation is picked up by the sensor, processed by computer and then displayed on the windshield using a **head-up display**.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Information is displayed as a black-and-white image with warmer objects in white, while cooler objects appear black.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] Because this system outputs a standard NTSC composite video signal and the used parts are somewhat easy and inexpensive to find, it has become a popular choice for fitting thermal night vision to other vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] After a long hiatus, the 2016 flagship Cadillac CT6 was equipped with an improved version of the Enhanced Night Vision, in which the images are displayed and embedded in the instrument panel instead of being displayed as a reflection on the windshield.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] In 2004, Honda introduced first worldwide system with pedestrian detection on redesigned Honda Legend: Intelligent Night Vision.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The pedestrian detection feature alerted the driver with an audio warning and visually enclosed the pedestrian in a box on the display which was presented via head-up display.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The night vision system uses a separate heads up type display projected on the center bottom of the windshield.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] The infrared cameras do not require a light source, and the software is able to detect human like figures, surround the image with a red box and give audible caution tones.
[src:adas-systems/automotive-night-vision] On the Peugeot 508, an optional night vision system helps to see pedestrians and animals during the night and alert the driver.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In road-transport terminology, a **lane departure warning system** (**LDWS**) is a mechanism designed to warn the driver when the vehicle begins to move out of its lane (unless a turn signal is on in that direction) on freeways and arterial roads.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] These systems are designed to minimize accidents by addressing the main causes of collisions: driver error, distractions and drowsiness.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) began studying whether to mandate lane departure warning systems and frontal collision warning systems on automobiles.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Another system is the emergency lane keeping (ELK).
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The emergency lane keeping applies correction to a vehicle which drifts beyond a solid lane marking.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] One of the main causes of single vehicle crashes and frontal crashes is lane departure.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The goal of the lateral support systems (LSS) is to help to avoid such crashes.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Without those LSS systems, lane departure can be unintentional; the car drifts towards and across the edge of the lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The car then reach a potentially dangerous situation.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This system does not work when the edge of the lane is not marked by a line.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] A lane detection system used behind the lane departure warning system uses the principle of Hough transform and Canny edge detector to detect lane lines from realtime camera images fed from the front-end camera of the automobile.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] A basic flowchart of how a lane detection algorithm works to help lane departure warning is shown in the figures.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In Europe, the lane departure warning system should be compatible with a visible lane marking identification standard such as commission regulation EU-351/2012.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The concept and a working model of this technology was invented and fitted to a Rover SD1 in England by British inventor Nick Parish in 1988.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The first production lane departure warning system in Europe was developed by the United States company Iteris for Mercedes Actros commercial trucks.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The system debuted in 2000, and is now available on many new cars, SUVs, and trucks.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In 2002, the Iteris system became available on Freightliner Trucks' North American vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In both these systems, the driver is warned of unintentional lane departures by an audible rumble strip sound generated on the side of the vehicle drifting out of the lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] No warnings are generated if, before crossing the lane, an active turn signal is given by the driver.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Nissan Motors began offering a lane-keeping support system on the Cima 450XV Limited (F500) sold in Japan.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Toyota introduced its lane monitoring system on models such as the Caldina and Alphard sold in Japan; this system warns the driver if it appears the vehicle is beginning to drift out of its lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Honda launched its Lane Keep Assist System (LKAS) on the Inspire.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] It provides up to 80% of steering torque to keep the car in its lane on the highway.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] It is also designed to make highway driving less cumbersome, by minimizing the driver's steering input.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] A camera, mounted at the top of the windshield just above the rear-view mirror, scans the road ahead in a 40-degree radius, picking up the dotted white lines used to divide lane boundaries on the highway.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The computer recognizes that the driver is "locked into" a particular lane, monitors how sharp a curve is, and uses factors such as yaw and vehicle speed to calculate the steering input required.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In 2004, the first passenger-vehicle system available in North America was jointly developed by Iteris and Valeo for Nissan on the Infiniti FX and (in 2005) the M vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In this system, a camera (mounted in the overhead console above the mirror) monitors the lane markings on a roadway.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] A warning tone is triggered to alert the driver when the vehicle begins to drift over the markings.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Also in 2004, Toyota added a lane keeping assist feature to the Crown Majesta which can apply a small counter-steering force to aid in keeping the vehicle in its lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Citroën became the first in Europe to offer LDWS on its 2005 C4 and C5 models, and its C6.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This system uses infrared sensors to monitor lane markings on the road surface, and a vibration mechanism in the seat alerts the driver of deviations.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Lexus introduced a multi-mode lane keeping assist system on the LS 460, which utilizes stereo cameras and more sophisticated object- and pattern-recognition processors.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This system can issue an audiovisual warning and also (using the electric power steering or EPS) steer the vehicle to hold its lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] It also applies counter-steering torque to help ensure the driver does not over-correct or "saw" the steering wheel while attempting to return the vehicle to its proper lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] If the radar cruise control system is engaged, the Lane Keep function works to help reduce the driver's steering-input burden by providing steering torque; however, the driver must remain active or the system will deactivate.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In 2007, Audi began offering its Audi lane assist feature for the first time on the Q7.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This system, unlike the Japanese "assist" systems, will not intervene in actual driving; rather, it will vibrate the steering wheel if the vehicle appears to be exiting its lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The LDW System in Audi is based on a forward-looking video-camera in its visible range, instead of the downward-looking infrared sensors in the Citroën.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Also in 2007, Infiniti offered a newer version of its 2004 system, which it called the Lane Departure Prevention (LDP) system.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This feature utilizes the vehicle stability control system to help assist the driver maintain lane position by applying gentle brake pressure on the appropriate wheels.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] General Motors introduced Lane Departure Warning on its 2008 model-year Cadillac STS, DTS, and Buick Lucerne models.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The General Motors system warns the driver with an audible tone and a warning indicator on the dashboard.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] BMW also introduced Lane Departure Warning on the 5 Series (E60) and 6 Series, using a vibrating steering wheel to warn the driver of unintended departures.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In late 2013 BMW updated the system with Traffic Jam Assistant appearing first on the redesigned BMW X5, this system works below 25 miles per hour (40 km/h).
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Volvo introduced the lane departure warning system and the driver alert control on its 2008 model-year S80, the V70, and XC70 executive cars.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Volvo's lane departure warning system uses a camera to track road markings and sound an alarm when drivers depart their lane without signaling.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The systems used by BMW, Volvo, and General Motors are based on core technology from Mobileye.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Mercedes-Benz began offering a Lane Keeping Assist function on the new E-class.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This system warns the driver (with a steering-wheel vibration) if it appears the vehicle is beginning to leave its lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Another feature will automatically deactivate and reactivate if it ascertains the driver is intentionally leaving his lane (for instance, aggressively cornering).
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] A newer version will use the braking system to assist in maintaining the vehicle's lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Kia Motors offered the 2011 Cadenza premium sedan with an optional lane departure warning system (LDWS) in limited markets.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This system uses a flashing dashboard icon and emits an audible warning when a white lane marking is being crossed, and emits a louder audible warning when a yellow-line marking is crossed.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This system is canceled when a turn signal is operating, or by pressing a deactivation switch on the dashboard; it works by using an optical sensor on both sides of the car.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Audi A7 introduces Audi active lane assist.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Mobileye developed a system that detected lane markings, and identified when a vehicle departed from its driving lane without the use of the turn signal.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Mercedes began Distronic Plus with Steering Assist and Stop&Go Pilot on the redesigned S-class in 2013.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Tesla Model S comes with advanced lane assistance systems with their 2014 release.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] It was also released with a speed assist feature where the front facing camera reads the traffic speed limits using the technology of computer vision character recognition system, and then conveys it to the car.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] On roads where traffic signs are absent, it relies on the GPS data.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] When the car moves away from a lane at above 30 miles per hour (48 km/h), the system beeps and the steering wheel vibrate, alerting the driver of an unintended lane change.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This happens during speed limit non-compliance as well.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Fiat is launching its lane keep assist feature based on TRW's lane keeping assist system (also known as the haptic lane feedback system).
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Introduced on the Lancia Delta in 2008, this system earned the Italian Automotive Technical Association's Best Automotive Innovation of the Year Award for 2008.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Peugeot introduced the same system as Citroën in its new 308.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Lane departure warning systems combine prevention with risk reports in the transportation industry.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Viewnyx applies video-based technology to assist fleets in lowering their driving liability costs.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] By providing safety managers with driver- and fleet-risk assessment reports and tools, it facilitates proactive coaching and training to eliminate high-risk behaviors.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The Lookout Solution is used by North American fleets, and there is research on implementing a lane departure warning system via a mobile phone.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] An Insurance Institute for Highway Safety raised concern that drivers may be less vigilant when relying on automated safety systems or become distracted by dashboard displays that monitor how the systems are performing.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Two separate studies found that lane-keeping systems and blind spot monitoring systems had lower crash rates than the same vehicles without the systems.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Police crash data from 25 states between 2009 and 2015 for vehicle models where the systems were sold as optional reduced rates of single-vehicle, sideswipe, and head-on crashes by 11 percent, and injuries in such crashes by 21 percent.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The sample size was not large enough to control for demographic and other variables.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Lane keeping assist (LKA) is a feature that, in addition to the lane departure warning system, automatically takes steps to ensure the vehicle stays in its lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Some vehicles combine adaptive cruise control with lane keeping systems to provide additional safety.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] While the combination of these features creates a semi-autonomous vehicle, most require the driver to remain in control of the vehicle while it is in use.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This is because of the limitations associated with the lane-keeping feature.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The lane keeping assist system is being achieved in modern vehicle systems using image processing techniques called Hough transform and Canny edge detection techniques.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] These advanced image processing techniques derive lane data from forward facing cameras attached to the front of the vehicle.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Real-time image processing using powerful computers like Nvidia's Drive PX1 are being used by many vehicle OEMs to achieve fully autonomous vehicles in which lane detection algorithm plays a key part.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Advanced lane detection algorithms are also being developed using deep learning and neural network techniques.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The neural network then will be able to change the steering angle based on the lane change on the road and keep the car in the middle of the lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] A lane keeping assist mechanism can either reactively turn a vehicle back into the lane if it starts to leave or proactively keep the vehicle in the center of the lane.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Vehicle companies often use the term "lane keep(ing) assist" to refer to both reactive lane keep assist (LKA) and proactive lane centering assist (LCA) but the terms are beginning to be differentiated.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] In 2020, UNECE released an automated lane keeping system (ALKS) regulation which include features such as lane-keeping and adaptative speed for specific roads up to 60 km/h.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] This feature has become more widespread since then, as seen below.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Lane keeping assist is mandatory for new cars and vans in the European Union as of 2022 under the name Emergency Lane Keeping System.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Lane departure warning systems and lane keeping systems rely on visible lane markings.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] They typically cannot decipher faded, missing, or incorrect lane markings.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Markings covered in snow or old lane markings left visible can hinder the ability of the system.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] UNECE regulation 130 does not require LDWS of heavy vehicles to work under 60 km/h or to work in a curve with a radius lower than 250 meters.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Lane departure warning systems also face many legal limitations regarding autonomous driving.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] As stated previously, this system requires constant driver input.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Vehicles with this technology are limited to assisting the driver, not driving the vehicle.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Lane departure warning systems biggest limitation is that it is not in complete control of the vehicle.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] The system does not take into account other vehicles on the road and "cannot replace good driving habits".
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] American Automobile Association testers found advanced driver assistance systems inconsistent and dangerous.
[src:adas-systems/lane-departure-warning-system] Systems performed 'mostly as expected', but when approaching a simulated disabled vehicle a collision occurred 66 per cent of the time and the average impact speed was 25 mph (40kmh).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] In this view, the viewer flies down to the rainforest canopy and flies through the virtual leaves.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This visualisation shows an airplane collecting a 50 km swathe of lidar data over the Brazilian rainforest.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] For ground-level features, colours range from deep brown to tan.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Vegetation heights are depicted in shades of green, where dark greens are closest to the ground and light greens are the highest.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar has terrestrial, airborne, and mobile uses.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] It is commonly used to make high-resolution maps, with applications in surveying, geodesy, geomatics, archaeology, geography, geology, geomorphology, seismology, forestry, atmospheric physics, laser guidance, airborne laser swathe mapping (ALSM), and laser altimetry.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] It is used to make digital 3-D representations of areas on the Earth's surface and ocean bottom of the intertidal and near coastal zone by varying the wavelength of light.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] It has also been increasingly used in control and navigation for autonomous cars and for the helicopter *Ingenuity* on its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar has since been used extensively for atmospheric research and meteorology.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar instruments fitted to aircraft and satellites carry out surveying and mapping – a recent example being the U.S.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Geological Survey Experimental Advanced Airborne Research Lidar.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] NASA has identified lidar as a key technology for enabling autonomous precision safe landing of future robotic and crewed lunar-landing vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The essential concept of lidar was originated by E.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Synge in 1930, who envisaged the use of powerful searchlights to probe the atmosphere.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Under the direction of Malcolm Stitch, the Hughes Aircraft Company introduced the first lidar-like system in 1961, shortly after the invention of the laser.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Intended for satellite tracking, this system combined laser-focused imaging with the ability to calculate distances by measuring the time for a signal to return using appropriate sensors and data acquisition electronics.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] It was originally called "Colidar" an acronym for "coherent light detecting and ranging", derived from the term "radar", itself an acronym for "radio detection and ranging".
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] All laser rangefinders, laser altimeters and lidar units are derived from the early colidar systems.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The first practical terrestrial application of a colidar system was the "Colidar Mark II", a large rifle-like laser rangefinder produced in 1963, which had a range of 11 km and an accuracy of 4.5 m, to be used for military targeting.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The first mention of lidar as a stand-alone word in 1963 suggests that it originated as a portmanteau of "light" and "radar": "Eventually the laser may provide an extremely sensitive detector of particular wavelengths from distant objects.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Meanwhile, it is being used to study the Moon by 'lidar' (light radar) ..." The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar's first applications were in meteorology, for which the National Center for Atmospheric Research used it to measure clouds and pollution.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The general public became aware of the accuracy and usefulness of lidar systems in 1971 during the Apollo 15 mission, when astronauts used a laser altimeter to map the surface of the Moon.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Although the English language no longer treats "radar" as an acronym, (i.e., uncapitalized), the word "lidar" was capitalized as "LIDAR" or "LiDAR" in some publications beginning in the 1980s.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Various publications refer to lidar as "LIDAR", "LiDAR", "LIDaR", or "Lidar".
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The USGS uses both "LIDAR" and "lidar", sometimes in the same document; the *New York Times* predominantly uses "lidar" for staff-written articles, although contributing news feeds such as Reuters may use Lidar.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar uses ultraviolet, visible, or near infrared light to image objects.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] It can target a wide range of materials, including non-metallic objects, rocks, rain, chemical compounds, aerosols, clouds and even single molecules.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A narrow laser beam can map physical features with very high resolutions; for example, an aircraft can map terrain at 30-centimetre (12 in) resolution or better.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Wavelengths vary to suit the target: from about 10 micrometers (infrared) to approximately 250 nanometers (ultraviolet).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Typically, light is reflected via backscattering, as opposed to pure reflection one might find with a mirror.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Different types of scattering are used for different lidar applications: most commonly Rayleigh scattering, Mie scattering, Raman scattering, and fluorescence.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Suitable combinations of wavelengths can allow remote mapping of atmospheric contents by identifying wavelength-dependent changes in the intensity of the returned signal.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The name "photonic radar" is sometimes used to mean visible-spectrum range finding like lidar, although photonic radar more strictly refers to radio-frequency range finding using photonics components.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] where *c* is the speed of light, *d* is the distance between the detector and the object or surface being detected, and *t* is the time spent for the laser light to travel to the object or surface being detected, then travel back to the detector.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The two kinds of lidar detection schemes are "incoherent" or direct energy detection (which principally measures amplitude changes of the reflected light) and coherent detection (best for measuring Doppler shifts, or changes in the phase of the reflected light).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Coherent systems generally use optical heterodyne detection.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This is more sensitive than direct detection and allows them to operate at much lower power, but requires more complex transceivers.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Both types employ pulse models: either *micropulse* or *high energy*.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Micropulse systems utilize intermittent bursts of energy.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] They developed as a result of ever-increasing computer power, combined with advances in laser technology.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] They use considerably less energy in the laser, typically on the order of one microjoule, and are often "eye-safe", meaning they can be used without safety precautions.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] 600–1,000 nm lasers are most common for non-scientific applications.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The maximum power of the laser is limited, or an automatic shut-off system which turns the laser off at specific altitudes is used in order to make it eye-safe for the people on the ground.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] One common alternative, 1,550 nm lasers, are eye-safe at relatively high power levels since this wavelength is strongly absorbed by water and barely reaches the retina, though camera sensors can still get damaged.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A trade-off though is that current detector technology is less advanced, so these wavelengths are generally used at longer ranges with lower accuracies.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] They are also used for military applications because 1,550 nm is not visible in night vision goggles, unlike the shorter 1,000 nm infrared laser.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Airborne topographic mapping lidars generally use 1,064 nm diode-pumped YAG lasers, while bathymetric (underwater depth research) systems generally use 532 nm frequency-doubled diode pumped YAG lasers because 532 nm penetrates water with much less attenuation than 1,064 nm.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Laser settings include the laser repetition rate (which controls the data collection speed).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Pulse length is generally an attribute of the laser cavity length, the number of passes required through the gain material (YAG, YLF, etc.), and Q-switch (pulsing) speed.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Better target resolution is achieved with shorter pulses, provided the lidar receiver detectors and electronics have sufficient bandwidth.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A phased array can illuminate any direction by using a microscopic array of individual antennas.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Controlling the timing (phase) of each antenna steers a cohesive signal in a specific direction.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Phased arrays have been used in radar since the 1940s.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] On the order of a million optical antennas are used to see a radiation pattern of a certain size in a certain direction.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] To achieve this the phase of each individual antenna (emitter) are precisely controlled.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] It is very difficult, if possible at all, to use the same technique in a lidar.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The main problems are that all individual emitters must be coherent (technically coming from the same "master" oscillator or laser source), have dimensions about the wavelength of the emitted light (1 micron range) to act as a point source with their phases being controlled with high accuracy.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Microelectromechanical mirrors (MEMS) are not entirely solid-state.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] However, their tiny form factor provides many of the same cost benefits.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A single laser is directed to a single mirror that can be reoriented to view any part of the target field.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] However, MEMS systems generally operate in a single plane (left to right).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] To add a second dimension generally requires a second mirror that moves up and down.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Alternatively, another laser can hit the same mirror from another angle.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] MEMS systems can be disrupted by shock/vibration and may require repeated calibration.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Image development speed is affected by the speed at which they are scanned.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Options to scan the azimuth and elevation include dual oscillating plane mirrors, a combination with a polygon mirror, and a dual axis scanner.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Optic choices affect the angular resolution and range that can be detected.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A hole mirror or a beam splitter are options to collect a return signal.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Two main photodetector technologies are used in lidar: solid-state photodetectors, such as silicon avalanche photodiodes, or photomultipliers.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The sensitivity of the receiver is another parameter that has to be balanced in a lidar design.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar sensors mounted on mobile platforms such as airplanes or satellites require instrumentation to determine the absolute position and orientation of the sensor.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Such devices generally include a Global Positioning System receiver and an inertial measurement unit (IMU).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar uses active sensors that supply their own illumination source.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The energy source hits objects and the reflected energy is detected and measured by sensors.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Distance to the object is determined by recording the time between transmitted and backscattered pulses and by using the speed of light to calculate the distance traveled.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Flash lidar allows for 3-D imaging because of the camera's ability to emit a larger flash and sense the spatial relationships and dimensions of area of interest with the returned energy.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This allows for more accurate imaging because the captured frames do not need to be stitched together, and the system is not sensitive to platform motion.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] 3-D imaging can be achieved using both scanning and non-scanning systems.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] "3-D gated viewing laser radar" is a non-scanning laser ranging system that applies a pulsed laser and a fast gated camera.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Research has begun for virtual beam steering using digital light processing (DLP) technology.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Imaging lidar can also be performed using arrays of high speed detectors and modulation sensitive detector arrays typically built on single chips using complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) and hybrid CMOS/charge-coupled device (CCD) fabrication techniques.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] In these devices each pixel performs some local processing such as demodulation or gating at high speed, downconverting the signals to video rate so that the array can be read like a camera.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Using this technique many thousands of pixels / channels may be acquired simultaneously.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] High resolution 3-D lidar cameras use homodyne detection with an electronic CCD or CMOS shutter.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A coherent imaging lidar uses synthetic array heterodyne detection to enable a staring single element receiver to act as though it were an imaging array.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] In 2014, Lincoln Laboratory announced a new imaging chip with more than 16,384 pixels, each able to image a single photon, enabling them to capture a wide area in a single image.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] An earlier generation of the technology with one fourth as many pixels was dispatched by the U.S. military after the January 2010 Haiti earthquake.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A single pass by a business jet at 3,000 m (10,000 ft) over Port-au-Prince was able to capture instantaneous snapshots of 600 m (2,000 ft) squares of the city at a resolution of 30 cm (1 ft), displaying the precise height of rubble strewn in city streets.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The new system is ten times better, and could produce much larger maps more quickly.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The chip uses indium gallium arsenide (InGaAs), which operates in the infrared spectrum at a relatively long wavelength that allows for higher power and longer ranges.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] In many applications, such as self-driving cars, the new system will lower costs by not requiring a mechanical component to aim the chip.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] InGaAs uses less hazardous wavelengths than conventional silicon detectors, which operate at visual wavelengths.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] New technologies for infrared single-photon counting lidar are advancing rapidly, including arrays and cameras in a variety of semiconductor and superconducting platforms.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar can be oriented to nadir, zenith, or laterally.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] For example, lidar altimeters look down, an atmospheric lidar looks up, and lidar-based collision avoidance systems are side-looking.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar applications can be divided into airborne and terrestrial types.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The two types require scanners with varying specifications based on the data's purpose, the size of the area to be captured, the range of measurement desired, the cost of equipment, and more.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Spaceborne platforms are also possible, see satellite laser altimetry.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar (also *airborne laser scanning*) is when a laser scanner, while attached to an aircraft during flight, creates a 3-D point cloud model of the landscape.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This is currently the most detailed and accurate method of creating digital elevation models, replacing photogrammetry.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] One major advantage in comparison with photogrammetry is the ability to filter out reflections from vegetation from the point cloud model to create a digital terrain model which represents ground surfaces such as rivers, paths, cultural heritage sites, etc., which are concealed by trees.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Within the category of airborne lidar, there is sometimes a distinction made between high-altitude and low-altitude applications, but the main difference is a reduction in both accuracy and point density of data acquired at higher altitudes.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar can also be used to create bathymetric models in shallow water.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The main constituents of airborne lidar include digital elevation models (DEM) and digital surface models (DSM).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The points and ground points are the vectors of discrete points while DEM and DSM are interpolated raster grids of discrete points.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The process also involves capturing of digital aerial photographs.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] To interpret deep-seated landslides for example, under the cover of vegetation, scarps, tension cracks or tipped trees airborne lidar is used.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar digital elevation models can see through the canopy of forest cover, perform detailed measurements of scarps, erosion and tilting of electric poles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar data is processed using a toolbox called Toolbox for Lidar Data Filtering and Forest Studies (TIFFS) for lidar data filtering and terrain study software.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The data is interpolated to digital terrain models using the software.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The laser is directed at the region to be mapped and each point's height above the ground is calculated by subtracting the original z-coordinate from the corresponding digital terrain model elevation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Based on this height above the ground the non-vegetation data is obtained which may include objects such as buildings, electric power lines, flying birds, insects, etc.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The rest of the points are treated as vegetation and used for modeling and mapping.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Within each of these plots, lidar metrics are calculated by calculating statistics such as mean, standard deviation, skewness, percentiles, quadratic mean, etc.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Multiple commercial lidar systems for unmanned aerial vehicles are currently on the market.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] These platforms can systematically scan large areas, or provide a cheaper alternative to manned aircraft for smaller scanning operations.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The airborne lidar bathymetric technological system involves the measurement of time of flight of a signal from a source to its return to the sensor.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The data acquisition technique involves a sea floor mapping component and a ground truth component that includes video transects and sampling.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] It works using a green spectrum (532 nm) laser beam.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Two beams are projected onto a fast rotating mirror, which creates an array of points.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] One of the beams penetrates the water and also detects the bottom surface of the water under favorable conditions.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Water depth measurable by lidar depends on the clarity of the water and the absorption of the wavelength used.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Water is most transparent to green and blue light, so these will penetrate deepest in clean water.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Blue-green light of 532 nm produced by frequency doubled solid-state IR laser output is the standard for airborne bathymetry.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This light can penetrate water but pulse strength attenuates exponentially with distance traveled through the water.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Lidar can measure depths from about 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft), with vertical accuracy in the order of 15 cm (6 in).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The surface reflection makes water shallower than about 0.9 m (3 ft) difficult to resolve, and absorption limits the maximum depth.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Turbidity causes scattering and has a significant role in determining the maximum depth that can be resolved in most situations, and dissolved pigments can increase absorption depending on wavelength.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Other reports indicate that water penetration tends to be between two and three times Secchi depth.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Bathymetric lidar is most useful in the 0–10 m (0–33 ft) depth range in coastal mapping.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] On average in fairly clear coastal seawater lidar can penetrate to about 7 m (23 ft), and in turbid water up to about 3 m (10 ft).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] An average value found by Saputra et al, 2021, is for the green laser light to penetrate water about one and a half to two times Secchi depth in Indonesian waters.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Water temperature and salinity have an effect on the refractive index which has a small effect on the depth calculation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The data obtained shows the full extent of the land surface exposed above the sea floor.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This technique is extremely useful as it will play an important role in the major sea floor mapping program.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The mapping yields onshore topography as well as underwater elevations.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Sea floor reflectance imaging is another solution product from this system which can benefit mapping of underwater habitats.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This technique has been used for three-dimensional image mapping of California's waters using a hydrographic lidar.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Airborne lidar systems were traditionally able to acquire only a few peak returns, while more recent systems acquire and digitize the entire reflected signal.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Scientists analysed the waveform signal for extracting peak returns using Gaussian decomposition.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Zhuang et al, 2017 used this approach for estimating aboveground biomass.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Handling the huge amounts of full-waveform data is difficult.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Therefore, Gaussian decomposition of the waveforms is effective, since it reduces the data and is supported by existing workflows that support interpretation of 3-D point clouds.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Recent studies investigated voxelisation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The intensities of the waveform samples are inserted into a voxelised space (3-D grayscale image) building up a 3-D representation of the scanned area.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Related metrics and information can then be extracted from that voxelised space.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Structural information can be extracted using 3-D metrics from local areas and there is a case study that used the voxelisation approach for detecting dead standing eucalypt trees in Australia.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Terrestrial applications of lidar (also *terrestrial laser scanning*) happen on the Earth's surface and can be either stationary or mobile.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Stationary terrestrial scanning is most common as a survey method, for example in conventional topography, monitoring, cultural heritage documentation and forensics.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The 3-D point clouds acquired from these types of scanners can be matched with digital images taken of the scanned area from the scanner's location to create realistic looking 3-D models in a relatively short time when compared to other technologies.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Each point in the point cloud is given the colour of the pixel from the image taken at the same location and direction as the laser beam that created the point.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Terrestrial lidar mapping involves a process of occupancy grid map generation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The process involves an array of cells divided into grids which employ a process to store the height values when lidar data falls into the respective grid cell.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] A binary map is then created by applying a particular threshold to the cell values for further processing.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] The next step is to process the radial distance and z-coordinates from each scan to identify which 3-D points correspond to each of the specified grid cell leading to the process of data formation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Mobile lidar (also *mobile laser scanning*) is when two or more scanners are attached to a moving vehicle to collect data along a path.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] These scanners are almost always paired with other kinds of equipment, including GNSS receivers and IMUs.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] One example application is surveying streets, where power lines, exact bridge heights, bordering trees, etc. all need to be taken into account.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] Instead of collecting each of these measurements individually in the field with a tachymeter, a 3-D model from a point cloud can be created where all of the measurements needed can be made, depending on the quality of the data collected.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p01] This eliminates the problem of forgetting to take a measurement, so long as the model is available, reliable and has an appropriate level of accuracy.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] There are a wide variety of lidar applications, in addition to the applications listed below, as it is often mentioned in national lidar dataset programs.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Companies are working to cut the cost of lidar sensors, currently anywhere from about US$1,200 to more than $12,000.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lower prices will make lidar more attractive for new markets.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Agricultural robots have been used for a variety of purposes ranging from seed and fertilizer dispersions, sensing techniques as well as crop scouting for the task of weed control.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar can help determine where to apply costly fertilizer.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] It can create a topographical map of the fields and reveal slopes and sun exposure of the farmland.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Researchers at the Agricultural Research Service used this topographical data with the farmland yield results from previous years, to categorize land into zones of high, medium, or low yield.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This indicates where to apply fertilizer to maximize yield.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar is now used to monitor insects in the field.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The use of lidar can detect the movement and behavior of individual flying insects, with identification down to sex and species.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2017 a patent application was published on this technology in the United States, Europe, and China.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Another application is crop mapping in orchards and vineyards, to detect foliage growth and the need for pruning or other maintenance, detect variations in fruit production, or count plants.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar is useful in GNSS-denied situations, such as nut and fruit orchards, where foliage causes interference for agriculture equipment that would otherwise utilize a precise GNSS fix.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors can detect and track the relative position of rows, plants, and other markers so that farming equipment can continue operating until a GNSS fix is reestablished.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Controlling weeds requires identifying plant species.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This can be done by using 3-D lidar and machine learning.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar produces plant contours as a "point cloud" with range and reflectance values.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This data is transformed, and features are extracted from it.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] If the species is known, the features are added as new data.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The species is labelled and its features are initially stored as an example to identify the species in the real environment.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This method is efficient because it uses a low-resolution lidar and supervised learning.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] It includes an easy-to-compute feature set with common statistical features which are independent of the plant size.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In April 2025, Dallas Fort Worth International Airport announced the deployment of a lidar-based platform for real-time monitoring of passenger and vehicle flows.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar has many uses in archaeology, including planning of field campaigns, mapping features under forest canopy, and overview of broad, continuous features indistinguishable from the ground.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar can produce high-resolution datasets quickly and cheaply.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar-derived products can be easily integrated into a geographic information system (GIS) for analysis and interpretation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar can also help to create high-resolution digital elevation models (DEMs) of archaeological sites that can reveal micro-topography that is otherwise hidden by vegetation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The intensity of the returned lidar signal can be used to detect features buried under flat vegetated surfaces such as fields, especially when mapping using the infrared spectrum.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The presence of these features affects plant growth and thus the amount of infrared light reflected back.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] For example, at Fort Beauséjour – Fort Cumberland National Historic Site, Canada, lidar discovered archaeological features related to the siege of the Fort in 1755.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Features that could not be distinguished on the ground or through aerial photography were identified by overlaying hill shades of the DEM created with artificial illumination from various angles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Another example is work at Caracol by Arlen Chase and his wife Diane Zaino Chase.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar was used to search for the legendary city of La Ciudad Blanca or "City of the Monkey God" in the La Mosquitia region of the Honduran jungle.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] During a seven-day mapping period, evidence was found of man-made structures.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In June 2013, the rediscovery of the city of Mahendraparvata was announced.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In southern New England, lidar was used to reveal stone walls, building foundations, abandoned roads, and other landscape features obscured in aerial photography by the region's dense forest canopy.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In Cambodia, lidar data were used by Damian Evans and Roland Fletcher to reveal anthropogenic changes to Angkor landscape.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2012, lidar revealed that the Purépecha settlement of Angamuco in Michoacán, Mexico had about as many buildings as today's Manhattan; while in 2016, its use in mapping ancient Maya causeways in northern Guatemala, revealed 17 elevated roads linking the ancient city of El Mirador to other sites.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2018, archaeologists using lidar discovered more than 60,000 man-made structures in the Maya Biosphere Reserve, a "major breakthrough" that showed the Maya civilization was much larger than previously thought.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2024, archaeologists using lidar discovered the Upano Valley sites.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Autonomous vehicles may use lidar for obstacle detection and avoidance to navigate safely through environments.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The introduction of lidar was a pivotal occurrence that was the key enabler behind Stanley, the first autonomous vehicle to successfully complete the DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Point cloud output from the lidar sensor provides the necessary data for robot software to determine where potential obstacles exist in the environment and where the robot is in relation to those potential obstacles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Singapore's *Singapore-MIT Alliance for Research and Technology (SMART)* is actively developing technologies for autonomous lidar vehicles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The very first generations of automotive adaptive cruise control systems used only lidar sensors.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In transportation systems, to ensure vehicle and passenger safety and to develop electronic systems that deliver driver assistance, understanding the vehicle and its surrounding environment is essential.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar systems play an important role in the safety of transportation systems.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Many electronic systems which enhance driver assistance and vehicle safety such as adaptive cruise control (ACC), emergency brake assist, and anti-lock braking system (ABS) depend on the detection of a vehicle's environment to act autonomously or semi-autonomously.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar mapping and estimation achieve this.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Current lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors which split the laser beam.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The upper three beams are used for vehicle and obstacles ahead, and the lower beams are used to detect lane markings and road features.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The major advantage of using lidar is that the spatial structure is obtained and this data can be fused with other sensors such as radar, etc. to get a better picture of the vehicle environment in terms of static and dynamic properties of the objects present in the environment.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Conversely, a significant issue with lidar is the difficulty in reconstructing point cloud data in poor weather conditions.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In heavy rain, for example, the light pulses emitted from the lidar system are partially reflected off of rain droplets which adds noise to the data, called 'echoes'.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Obstacle detection and road environment recognition using lidar, proposed by Kun Zhou et al. not only focuses on object detection and tracking but also recognizes lane marking and road features.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] As mentioned earlier, the lidar systems use rotating hexagonal mirrors that split the laser beam into six beams.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The upper three layers are used to detect the forward objects such as vehicles and roadside objects.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The sensor is made of weather-resistant material.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The data detected by lidar are clustered to several segments and tracked by Kalman filter.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Data clustering here is done based on characteristics of each segment based on object model, which distinguish different objects such as vehicles, signboards, etc.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] These characteristics include the dimensions of the object, etc.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The reflectors on the rear edges of vehicles are used to differentiate vehicles from other objects.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Object tracking is done using a two-stage Kalman filter considering the stability of tracking and the accelerated motion of objects Lidar reflective intensity data is also used for curb detection by making use of robust regression to deal with occlusions.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Road marking is detected using a modified Otsu method by distinguishing rough and shiny surfaces.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Roadside reflectors that indicate lane border are sometimes hidden due to various reasons.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Therefore, other information is needed to recognize the road border.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The lidar used in this method can measure the reflectivity from the object.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Hence, with this data the road border can also be recognized.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Also, the usage of a sensor with a weather-robust head helps to detect the objects even in bad weather conditions.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Canopy height model before and after a flood is a good example.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar can detect highly detailed canopy height data as well as its road border.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar measurements help identify the spatial structure of the obstacle.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This helps distinguish objects based on size and estimate the impact of driving over it.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar systems provide better range and a large field of view, which helps in detecting obstacles on the curves.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This is one of its major advantages over radar systems, which have a narrower field of view.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The fusion of lidar measurement with different sensors makes the system robust and useful in real-time applications, since lidar-dependent systems cannot estimate the dynamic information about the detected object.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] It has been shown that lidar can be manipulated, such that self-driving cars are tricked into taking evasive action.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar has also found many applications for mapping natural and managed landscapes such as forests, wetlands, and grasslands.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Canopy heights, biomass measurements, and leaf area can all be studied using airborne lidar systems.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Similarly, lidar is also used by many industries, including Energy and Railroad, and the Department of Transportation as a faster way of surveying.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Topographic maps can also be generated readily from lidar, including for recreational use such as in the production of orienteering maps.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been applied to estimate and assess the biodiversity of plants, fungi, and animals.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Using southern bull kelp in New Zealand, coastal lidar mapping data has been compared with population genomic evidence to form hypotheses regarding the occurrence and timing of prehistoric earthquake uplift events.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar systems have also been applied to improve forestry management.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Measurements are used to take inventory in forest plots as well as calculate individual tree heights, crown width and crown diameter.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Other statistical analysis use lidar data to estimate total plot information such as canopy volume, mean, minimum and maximum heights, vegetation cover, biomass, and carbon density.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Aerial lidar was used to map the bush fires in Australia in early 2020.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The data was manipulated to view bare earth, and identify healthy and burned vegetation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] High-resolution digital elevation maps generated by airborne and stationary lidar have led to significant advances in geomorphology (the branch of geoscience concerned with the origin and evolution of the Earth surface topography).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2005 the Tour Ronde in the Mont Blanc massif became the first high alpine mountain on which lidar was employed to monitor the increasing occurrence of severe rock-fall over large rock faces allegedly caused by climate change and degradation of permafrost at high altitude.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used in structural geology and geophysics as a combination between airborne lidar and GNSS for the detection and study of faults, for measuring uplift.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The output of the two technologies can produce extremely accurate elevation models for terrain – models that can even measure ground elevation through trees.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This combination was used most famously to find the location of the Seattle Fault in Washington, United States.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This combination also measures uplift at Mount St.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Helens by using data from before and after the 2004 uplift.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar systems monitor glaciers and have the ability to detect subtle amounts of growth or decline.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A satellite-based system, the NASA ICESat, includes a lidar sub-system for this purpose.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The NASA Airborne Topographic Mapper is also used extensively to monitor glaciers and perform coastal change analysis.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The combination is also used by soil scientists while creating a soil survey.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The detailed terrain modeling allows soil scientists to see slope changes and landform breaks which indicate patterns in soil spatial relationships.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Initially, based on ruby lasers, lidar for meteorological applications was constructed shortly after the invention of the laser and represents one of the first applications of laser technology.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar technology has since expanded vastly in capability and lidar systems are used to perform a range of measurements that include profiling clouds, measuring winds, studying aerosols, and quantifying various atmospheric components.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Atmospheric components can in turn provide useful information including surface pressure (by measuring the absorption of oxygen or nitrogen), greenhouse gas emissions (carbon dioxide and methane), photosynthesis (carbon dioxide), fires (carbon monoxide), and humidity (water vapor).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Atmospheric lidars can be either ground-based, airborne or satellite-based depending on the type of measurement.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] 2. by measuring the scattered reflection off the ground (when the lidar is airborne) or other hard surface.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Backscatter from the atmosphere directly gives a measure of clouds and aerosols.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Other derived measurements from backscatter such as winds or cirrus ice crystals require careful selecting of the wavelength and/or polarization detected.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] *Doppler lidar* and *Rayleigh Doppler lidar* are used to measure temperature and wind speed along the beam by measuring the frequency of the backscattered light.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The Doppler broadening of gases in motion allows the determination of properties via the resulting frequency shift.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Scanning lidars, such as NASA's conical-scanning HARLIE, have been used to measure atmospheric wind velocity.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The ESA wind mission *ADM-Aeolus* will be equipped with a Doppler lidar system in order to provide global measurements of vertical wind profiles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A doppler lidar system was used in the 2008 Summer Olympics to measure wind fields during the yacht competition.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Doppler lidar systems are also now beginning to be successfully applied in the renewable energy sector to acquire wind speed, turbulence, wind veer, and wind shear data.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Both pulsed and continuous wave systems are being used.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Pulsed systems use signal timing to obtain vertical distance resolution, whereas continuous wave systems rely on detector focusing.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The term *eolics* has been proposed to describe the collaborative and interdisciplinary study of wind using computational fluid mechanics simulations and Doppler lidar measurements.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The ground reflection of an airborne lidar gives a measure of surface reflectivity (assuming the atmospheric transmittance is well known) at the lidar wavelength, however, the ground reflection is typically used for making absorption measurements of the atmosphere.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] "Differential absorption lidar" (DIAL) measurements utilize two or more closely spaced (less than 1 nm) wavelengths to factor out surface reflectivity as well as other transmission losses, since these factors are relatively insensitive to wavelength.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] When tuned to the appropriate absorption lines of a particular gas, DIAL measurements can be used to determine the concentration (mixing ratio) of that particular gas in the atmosphere.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This is referred to as an *integrated path differential absorption* (IPDA) approach, since it is a measure of the integrated absorption along the entire lidar path.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars can be either pulsed or CW and typically use two or more wavelengths.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] IPDA lidars have been used for remote sensing of carbon dioxide and methane.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In Japan, differential absorption lidar (DIAL) and Raman lidar technologies are being developed to improve the accuracy of flood forecasting and rainfall prediction.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A research by several companies, universities, and institutes, led by Kyushu University is conducting work on meteorological sensing and flood-risk modelling under a government program.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In May 2025, EKO Instruments began a field study on Goto Fukue Island, Nagasaki Prefecture, using a Micropulse DIAL lidar system provided by the National Center for Atmospheric Research (NSF NCAR).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The study compares DIAL performance with existing Raman lidar systems.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Ltd. signed a technology license agreement in February 2025 with Montana State University, NSF NCAR, and NASA, covering key DIAL-related patents.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Few military applications are known to be in place and are classified (such as the lidar-based speed measurement of the AGM-129 ACM stealth nuclear cruise missile), but a considerable amount of research is underway in their use for imaging.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Higher resolution systems collect enough detail to identify targets, such as tanks.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Examples of military applications of lidar include the Airborne Laser Mine Detection System (ALMDS) for counter-mine warfare by Areté Associates.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A NATO report (RTO-TR-SET-098) evaluated the potential technologies to do stand-off detection for the discrimination of biological warfare agents.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The potential technologies evaluated were long-wave infrared (LWIR), differential scattering (DISC), and ultraviolet laser-induced fluorescence (UV-LIF).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Short-range compact spectrometric lidar based on laser-induced fluorescence (LIF) would address the presence of bio-threats in aerosol form over critical indoor, semi-enclosed and outdoor venues such as stadiums, subways, and airports.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This near real-time capability would enable rapid detection of a bioaerosol release and allow for timely implementation of measures to protect occupants and minimize the extent of contamination.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The Long-Range Biological Standoff Detection System (LR-BSDS) was developed for the U.S.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Army to provide the earliest possible standoff warning of a biological attack.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] It is an airborne system carried by helicopter to detect synthetic aerosol clouds containing biological and chemical agents at long range.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The LR-BSDS, with a detection range of 30 km or more, was fielded in June 1997.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Five lidar units produced by the German company Sick AG were used for short range detection on Stanley, the autonomous car that won the 2005 DARPA Grand Challenge.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A robotic Boeing AH-6 performed a fully autonomous flight in June 2010, including avoiding obstacles using lidar.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The calculation of ore volumes is accomplished by periodic (monthly) scanning in areas of ore removal, then comparing surface data to the previous scan.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar sensors may also be used for obstacle detection and avoidance for robotic mining vehicles such as in the Komatsu Autonomous Haulage System (AHS) used in Rio Tinto's Mine of the Future.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A worldwide network of observatories uses lidars to measure the distance to reflectors placed on the Moon, allowing the position of the Moon to be measured with millimeter precision and tests of general relativity to be done.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] MOLA, the Mars Orbiting Laser Altimeter, used a lidar instrument in a Mars-orbiting satellite (the NASA Mars Global Surveyor) to produce a spectacularly precise global topographic survey of the red planet.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Laser altimeters produced global elevation models of Mars, the Moon (Lunar Orbiter Laser Altimeter (LOLA)), and Mercury (Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA), NEAR–Shoemaker Laser Rangefinder (NLR)).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Future missions will also include laser altimeter experiments such as the Ganymede Laser Altimeter (GALA) as part of the Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) mission.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In September, 2008, the NASA *Phoenix* lander used lidar to detect snow in the atmosphere of Mars.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In atmospheric physics, lidar is used as a remote detection instrument to measure densities of certain constituents of the middle and upper atmosphere, such as potassium, sodium, or molecular nitrogen and oxygen.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] These measurements can be used to calculate temperatures.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to measure wind speed and to provide information about vertical distribution of the aerosol particles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] At the JET nuclear fusion research facility in the UK near Abingdon, Oxfordshire, lidar Thomson scattering is used to determine electron density and temperature profiles of the plasma.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar has been widely used in rock mechanics for rock mass characterization and slope change detection.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Some important geomechanical properties from the rock mass can be extracted from the 3-D point clouds obtained by means of the lidar.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Some of these properties have been used to assess the geomechanical quality of the rock mass through the RMR index.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Moreover, as the orientations of discontinuities can be extracted using the existing methodologies, it is possible to assess the geomechanical quality of a rock slope through the SMR index.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In addition to this, the comparison of different 3-D point clouds from a slope acquired at different times allows researchers to study the changes produced on the scene during this time interval as a result of rockfalls or any other landsliding processes.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] THOR is a laser designed toward measuring Earth's atmospheric conditions.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The laser enters a cloud cover and measures the thickness of the return halo.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The sensor has a fiber optic aperture with a width of 7+1⁄2 inches (19 cm) that is used to measure the return light.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar technology is being used in robotics for the perception of the environment as well as object classification.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The ability of lidar technology to provide three-dimensional elevation maps of the terrain, high precision distance to the ground, and approach velocity can enable safe landing of robotic and crewed vehicles with a high degree of precision.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar is also widely used in robotics for simultaneous localization and mapping and is well-integrated into robot simulators.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Refer to the Military section above for further examples.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar is increasingly being utilized for rangefinding and orbital element calculation of relative velocity in proximity operations and stationkeeping of spacecraft.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar has also been used for atmospheric studies from space.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Short pulses of laser light beamed from a spacecraft can reflect off tiny particles in the atmosphere and back to a telescope aligned with the spacecraft laser.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] By precisely timing the lidar echo, and by measuring how much laser light is received by the telescope, scientists can accurately determine the location, distribution and nature of the particles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The result is a revolutionary new tool for studying constituents in the atmosphere, from cloud droplets to industrial pollutants, which are difficult to detect by other means.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Laser altimetry is used to make digital elevation maps of planets, including the Mars Orbital Laser Altimeter (MOLA) mapping of Mars, the Lunar Orbital Laser Altimeter (LOLA) and Lunar Altimeter (LALT) mapping of the Moon, and the Mercury Laser Altimeter (MLA) mapping of Mercury.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] It is also used to help navigate the helicopter *Ingenuity* in its record-setting flights over the terrain of Mars.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Airborne lidar sensors are used by companies in the remote sensing field.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] They can be used to create a DTM (digital terrain model) or DEM (digital elevation model); this is quite a common practice for larger areas as a plane can acquire 3–4 km (2–2+1⁄2 mi) wide swaths in a single flyover.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Greater vertical accuracy of below 50 mm (2 in) can be achieved with a lower flyover, even in forests, where it is able to give the height of the canopy as well as the ground elevation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Typically, a GNSS receiver configured over a georeferenced control point is needed to link the data in with the WGS (World Geodetic System).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar is also in use in hydrographic surveying.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Depending upon the clarity of the water lidar can measure depths from 0.9 to 40 m (3 to 131 ft) with a vertical accuracy of 15 cm (6 in) and horizontal accuracy of 2.5 m (8 ft).
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in the railroad industry to generate asset health reports for asset management and by departments of transportation to assess their road conditions.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] CivilMaps.com is a leading company in the field.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar has been used in adaptive cruise control (ACC) systems for automobiles.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Systems such as those by Siemens, Hella, Ouster and Cepton use a lidar device mounted on the front of the vehicle, such as the bumper, to monitor the distance between the vehicle and any vehicle in front of it.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In the event where the vehicle in front slows down or is too close, the ACC applies the brakes to slow the vehicle.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] When the road ahead is clear, the ACC allows the vehicle to accelerate to a speed preset by the driver.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A lidar-based device, the Ceilometer, is used at airports worldwide to measure the height of clouds on runway approach paths.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar can be used to increase the energy output from wind farms by accurately measuring wind speeds and wind turbulence.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Experimental lidar systems can be mounted on the nacelle of a wind turbine or integrated into the rotating spinner to measure oncoming horizontal winds, winds in the wake of the wind turbine, and proactively adjust blades to protect components and increase power.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar is also used to characterise the incident wind resource for comparison with wind turbine power production to verify the performance of the wind turbine by measuring the wind turbine's power curve.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Wind farm optimization can be considered a topic in *applied eolics*.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Another aspect of lidar in wind related industry is to use computational fluid dynamics over lidar-scanned surfaces in order to assess the wind potential, which can be used for optimal wind farm placement.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar can also be used to assist planners and developers in optimizing solar photovoltaic systems at the city level by determining appropriate roof tops and for determining shading losses.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Recent airborne laser scanning efforts have focused on ways to estimate the amount of solar light hitting vertical building facades, or by incorporating more detailed shading losses by considering the influence from vegetation and larger surrounding terrain.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The 2017 exploration game *Scanner Sombre*, by Introversion Software, uses lidar as a fundamental game mechanic.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In *Build the Earth*, lidar is used to create accurate renders of terrain in *Minecraft* to account for any errors (mainly regarding elevation) in the default generation.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The process of rendering terrain into Build the Earth is limited by the amount of data available in region as well as the speed it takes to convert the file into block data.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Lidar technology enhances physical security by providing precise, privacy-compliant threat detection for applications such as perimeter protection, building facades, and critical infrastructure monitoring.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] These systems utilize laser-based sensors to create high-density point clouds that function reliably in challenging environmental conditions, including rain, snow, and complete darkness.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] A key advantage of modern systems is the use of 3D lidar, which creates precise volumetric detection zones capturing height, width, and depth, allowing for the accurate classification of object size and movement speed.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The video for the 2007 song "House of Cards" by Radiohead was believed to be the first use of real-time 3-D laser scanning to record a music video.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The range data in the video is not completely from a lidar, as structured light scanning is also used.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2020, Apple introduced the fourth generation of iPad Pro with a lidar sensor integrated into the rear camera module, especially developed for augmented reality (AR) experiences.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The feature was later included in the iPhone 12 Pro lineup and subsequent Pro models.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] On Apple devices, lidar empowers portrait mode pictures with night mode, quickens auto focus and improves accuracy in the Measure app.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In 2022, *Wheel of Fortune* started using lidar technology to track when Vanna White moves her hand over the puzzle board to reveal letters.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The first episode to have this technology was in the season 40 premiere.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In flash lidar, the entire field of view is illuminated with a wide diverging laser beam in a single pulse.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This is in contrast to conventional scanning lidar, which uses a collimated laser beam that illuminates a single point at a time, and the beam is raster scanned to illuminate the field of view point-by-point.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] This illumination method requires a different detection scheme as well.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In both scanning and flash lidar, a time-of-flight camera is used to collect information about both the 3-D location and intensity of the light incident on it in every frame.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] However, in scanning lidar, this camera contains only a point sensor, while in flash lidar, the camera contains either a 1-D or a 2-D sensor array, each pixel of which collects 3-D location and intensity information.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] In both cases, the depth information is collected using the time of flight of the laser pulse (i.e., the time it takes each laser pulse to hit the target and return to the sensor), which requires the pulsing of the laser and acquisition by the camera to be synchronized.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The result is a camera that takes pictures of distance, instead of colors.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Flash lidar is especially advantageous when compared to scanning lidar, when the camera, scene, or both are moving, since the entire scene is illuminated at the same time.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] With scanning lidar, motion can cause "jitter" from the lapse in time as the laser rasters over the scene.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] As with all forms of lidar, the onboard source of illumination makes flash lidar an active sensor.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The signal that is returned is processed by embedded algorithms to produce a nearly instantaneous 3-D rendering of objects and terrain features within the field of view of the sensor.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The laser pulse repetition frequency is sufficient for generating 3-D videos with high resolution and accuracy.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The high frame rate of the sensor makes it a useful tool for a variety of applications that benefit from real-time visualization, such as highly precise remote landing operations.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] By immediately returning a 3-D elevation mesh of target landscapes, a flash sensor can be used to identify optimal landing zones in autonomous spacecraft landing scenarios.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Seeing at a distance requires a powerful burst of light.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] The power is limited to levels that do not damage human retinas.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] However, low-cost silicon imagers do not read light in the eye-safe spectrum.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Instead, gallium-arsenide imagers are required, which can boost costs to $200,000.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Gallium-arsenide is the same compound used to produce high-cost, high-efficiency solar panels usually used in space applications.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] Computer stereo vision has shown promise as an alternative to lidar for close-range applications.
[src:adas-systems/lidar-p02] It is significantly more cost effective when appropriate.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] The data sources for a fusion process are not specified to originate from identical sensors.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] One can distinguish *direct fusion*, *indirect fusion* and fusion of the outputs of the former two.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Direct fusion is the fusion of sensor data from a set of heterogeneous or homogeneous sensors, soft sensors, and history values of sensor data, while indirect fusion uses information sources like *a priori* knowledge about the environment and human input.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion is also known as *(multi-sensor) data fusion* and is a subset of *information fusion*.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Two example sensor fusion calculations are illustrated below.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Let ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ denote two estimates from two independent sensor measurements, with noise variances $\scriptstyle \sigma _{1}^{2}$ and $\scriptstyle \sigma _{2}^{2}$ , respectively.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] It can be seen that the fused result is simply a linear combination of the two measurements weighted by their respective information.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] It is worth noting that if ${x}$ is a random variable.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] The estimates ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ will be correlated through common process noise, which will cause the estimate ${x}_{3}$ to lose conservativeness.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Another (equivalent) method to fuse two measurements is to use the optimal Kalman filter.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Suppose that the data is generated by a first-order system and let ${\textbf {P}}_{k}$ denote the solution of the filter's Riccati equation.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] By inspection, when the first measurement is noise free, the filter ignores the second measurement and vice versa.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] That is, the combined estimate is weighted by the quality of the measurements.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] In sensor fusion, centralized versus decentralized refers to where the fusion of the data occurs.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] In centralized fusion, the clients simply forward all of the data to a central location, and some entity at the central location is responsible for correlating and fusing the data.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] In decentralized, the clients take full responsibility for fusing the data.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Multiple combinations of centralized and decentralized systems exist.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Another classification of sensor configuration refers to the coordination of information flow between sensors.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] These mechanisms provide a way to resolve conflicts or disagreements and to allow the development of dynamic sensing strategies.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Sensors are in redundant (or competitive) configuration if each node delivers independent measures of the same properties.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] This configuration can be used in error correction when comparing information from multiple nodes.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Redundant strategies are often used with high level fusions in voting procedures.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Complementary configuration occurs when multiple information sources supply different information about the same features.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] This strategy is used for fusing information at raw data level within decision-making algorithms.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Complementary features are typically applied in motion recognition tasks with neural network, hidden Markov model, support vector machine, clustering methods and other techniques.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor fusion uses the information extracted by multiple independent sensors to provide information that would not be available from single sensors.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] For example, sensors connected to body segments are used for the detection of the angle between them.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor strategy gives information impossible to obtain from single nodes.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Cooperative information fusion can be used in motion recognition, gait analysis, motion analysis,,.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] There are several categories or levels of sensor fusion that are commonly used.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion level can also be defined basing on the kind of information used to feed the fusion algorithm.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] More precisely, sensor fusion can be performed fusing raw data coming from different sources, extrapolated features or even decision made by single nodes.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] One application of sensor fusion is GPS/INS, where Global Positioning System and inertial navigation system data is fused using various different methods, e.g. the extended Kalman filter.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] This is useful, for example, in determining the attitude of an aircraft using low-cost sensors.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Another example is using the data fusion approach to determine the traffic state (low traffic, traffic jam, medium flow) using road side collected acoustic, image and sensor data.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] In the field of autonomous driving, sensor fusion is used to combine the redundant information from complementary sensors in order to obtain a more accurate and reliable representation of the environment.
[src:adas-systems/sensor-fusion] Although technically not a dedicated sensor fusion method, modern convolutional neural network based methods can simultaneously process many channels of sensor data (such as hyperspectral imaging with hundreds of bands ) and fuse relevant information to produce classification results.
